<br>
Triff, and the other person quoting Ayn Rand, you've both made a serious error in the process of determining what is 'right' in this situation.<br>
<br>
I'll agree with most of your supporting arguments, but unfortunately, your mistake makes your conclusion invalid.  I agree that A is A, that man's primary interest necessarily must be himself, that no amount of *need* will present a claim on another man's life, etc., etc., etc.  Your flaw is thus:<br>
<br>
As a reasoning adult, you have engaged in a contract with the United States of America, to be a citizen of this country, and as such, have agreed to the terms of the Selective Service document you *willingly* signed.  You, as a reasoning individual, were presented with a choice:  citizenship in the USA, departure/exile/non-citizenship (I actually don't know what happens if you don't agree, but it should be exile at a minimum, IMHO).<br>
<br>
If you are as well read in Rand's writing as I believe you to be, remember that the view of Objectivism, is that Government has only 2 primary functions:  protection of it's Citizens, and protection of it's Property.  When I sign the contract to be a Citizen, I then hold my country responsible for protection of MY body, and MY property, and it holds me responsible to answer a call to duty, when required.  The draft is that call.<br>
<br>
YOU signed the contract.<br>
YOU are the individual with whom the government made this agreement.<br>
YOU accept the protection of your person and your property by the military, police forces, courts and other services provided by this country.<br>
YOU should answer the call if it's made.<br>
<br>
Paying taxes isn't enough.  That pays for the buildings and the employees, what maintains freedom to think, act, and speak?  The concept that IS America, and it is bought with the agreement that when called, it's citizens will answer.<br>
<br>
If you disagree with your contract, now that you are better informed, renounce your citizenship, as a rational, selfish individual must.  By staying in this country, dishonoring this contract (even if it's only speculation of a draft), you make yourself the most unreasonable of all.  The Hypocrite.  You'll rail against selflessness, altruism, evil, etc., but it will all be hollow, because you'll know that you are no longer a man (or woman) of your word.<br>
<br>
The choice is very simple.<br>
<br>
As a final note, to everyone else, blind support of any action is even more foolish than the mistakes made by these 2 guys who simply missed a point in their logic.  At least they 'are' thinking individuals, who I assume, listen to reason.  Putting on the blinders doesn't help.<br>
<br>
